<br>
The reason to join a guild is to acomplish goals that one cannot accomplish on their own. Is it possible to gt friends to help with a big quest now and then for a guildless person? Of course it is, but guilds will soon get tired of helping the same person that isnt a member. <br>
<br>
Most guilds have raid loot policies denying applicants and probationary members from aquiring loot on raids until the guild decides that they are useful members of the guild. Why then, would a guild consistantly raid for a nonguilded toon.<br>
<br>
Now, I have, along with my guild, helped MANY nonguilded players as well as those from other guilds, but the focus of my guild is for US to have fun and increase OUR abilities so WE can do new and exciting things...in turn having more fun.<br>
<br>
In short, if you want your epic, join a guild, attend their raids, be friendly in /gu, become a valuable member of said guild, and they will come to you wanting to help on the big parts of your epic.<br>
<br>
As far as the limit of 6 members from a single posting entity, I believe the resaoning is to ensure that a givin small guild isnt reserving a plane for a larger guild so they can be there more often. If you reserve a plane, you need to have sufficient force to enter and fight it, and take the responsibility to ensure that it is cleared (by someone if not yourself). This is really a guess as Ive never seen the reasoning behind this rule, but Im ok with it for this simple reason. <p>Hutterr Verbruggen

